{\rtf1\ansi \deff0{\fonttbl{\f8\fswiss Arial;}}\margl720\margr2160\pgnstart32\sectd\pgnrestart\pgnstarts32\footery1080{\header \pard\plain\ql MYARC ADVANCED BASIC\par }{\footer \pard\plain\ql \chpgn     VERSION 4.0  DDI SOFTWARE  \par }\pard \plain\f8\fs20 CLS\tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab CLS\par \par \par \par \par Format\par CLS\par \par Description\par You may use CLS either as a program statement or a command.\par \par CLS clears the screen or window created with the CALL MARGINS statement, and returns the cursor\par to the home position.\par \par Examples\par \par 100 CALL GRAPHICS(2,1)\par 110 CALL MARGINS(1,24,1,40)\par 120 CALL HCHAR(1,1,ASC("A"),960)\par 130 CALL MARGINS(5,10,5,10)\par 140 CLS\par 150 CALL KEY(0,K,S)::IF S<1 THEN 150\par RUN\par \par Program will fill screen with character 65, the letter A, then it creates a window 5 rows by 5 columns.\par The CLS statement clears this window leaving the remainder of the screen filled with the letter "A".\par \par NOTE: An alternate method of clearing the active "window" in this case would have been to substitute\par line 140 with:\par \par 140 DISPLAY AT(1,1)ERASE ALL:""\par \par CALL CLEAR or CALL GRAPHICS(n[n1,n2]) will clear the entire screen.\par }
